DATA
Discussed above.
IMPRESSION/PLAN
#1 Hepatic flexure colon mass
This is concerning clinically for a malignancy although we do not have pathologic evidence.  Dr. Carey Stein has reviewed the information regarding Mr. Ralston and would like us to proceed with a colonoscopy with biopsy of the lesion and a staging CT-scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis.  We will get a CEA as well.  Discussed likely surgery being a right hemicolectomy versus an extended right hemicolectomy depending on the location of the mass.  Also discussed if this is found to be a malignancy that based on the surgical pathology he may need additional treatment with adjuvant chemotherapy.  With his early-onset of likely colon cancer, I discussed with him the potential for testing for HNPCC (Lynch syndrome) and gave him a pamphlet on MSI/IHC testing as well as the HNPCC pamphlet.  After discussing the IHC/MSI testing as initial screening tests with Mr. Ralston and his sister, Dr. Stahl, he would like to go ahead and proceed.  If this is found to be a malignancy on biopsy, we can proceed with this and hopefully have the IHC results back by Monday when he sees Dr. Stein.  We will tentatively plan for surgery next week depending on his evaluation.  I discussed with him all of his sisters should have colonoscopies if they have not done so, and at this time he does not have children.   I discussed with him to stop taking  ibuprofen and instead if he has discomfort to use Tylenol because of his bleeding.
#2 Hypertension
Well-controlled.  Recent adjustment in medications.
#3 Anemia likely related to No. 1
Will get type and screen as well as CBC.
#4 Hyperlipidemia
Well-controlled.
#5 Obesity
#6 PAME
Will get a baseline EKG with his early family history of heart disease with his father as well as his risk factors including obesity, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia.  Otherwise he is generally active.  Unless this is abnormal, I do not feel a stress test is indicated.
He was seen with his sister.  All questions were answered.  Sixty minutes spent.  Given laparoscopic colon book.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
Code status:  Discussed with Mr. Ralston, and he would like to be a full code.

