[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Ralston is a 48-year-old male from 53912, who is the brother of Dr. Lee Stahl in Pathology here at JSEIMC.  Mr. Ralston went in for his annual physical and had discussed with his local provider that for the last five to six-months he has been having intermittent rectal bleeding.  He noticed his stools were "reddish."  This did not happen very often, just a few times a month.  He also noticed that his stools became a little more loose although they were not diarrhea.  He was still going two-to-three times a day which was his norm.  He denies fecal incontinence.  He had blood work performed as part of his evaluation which revealed a hemoglobin of 10.2 with a hematocrit of 33.8 on April 12, 2010.  His hemoglobin was suspected to be normal approximately a year ago.  He had never had colon screening and has no family history of colon cancer but proceeded to a colonoscopy locally on April 20, 2010 revealing a circumferential mass at the hepatic flexure.  The endoscope was not able to be passed beyond this.  This appeared "frankly malignant."  SPOT injection was used to mark the area.  He also had a small transverse colon polyp that was removed with a cold snare.  They did not biopsy the hepatic flexure lesion.  We also do not have pathology from the other small transverse colon polyp.  He has not undergone further evaluation and is here for definitive treatment.
Mr. Ralston also had noticed "a pressure sensation" in the low pelvis and a little more gas pain.  He would not call this pain.  He had also had intermittent problems prior to going in for evaluation with anal pain with defecation rating a 6 on the pain scale and then he would be sore for several hours afterward.  He does not remember being constipated.  He thought initially that this was where the bleeding was coming from and that maybe he had a tear at the anus.  His appetite has been good although he has lost 10 to 15 pounds intentionally over the last six-months with doing more walking, exercising, and watching his diet.  He denies recent nausea or vomiting.  He has not felt more fatigued and works as an IT specialist.

